df = (pd.read_csv("../data/raw/coinbaseUSD_1-min_data_2014-12-01_to_2018-11-11.csv", 
      usecols=['Timestamp', 'Weighted_Price', 'Volume_(BTC)'])
      .rename(columns={'Volume_(BTC)': 'Volume', 'Volume_(Currency)': 'Dollars', 'Timestamp': 'TS', 'Weighted_Price': 'Price'})
      .assign(Timestamp=lambda df: (pd.to_datetime(df['TS'], unit='s')))
      .assign(DollarVol=lambda df: df['Price']*df['Volume'])

def log_returns(s):
    returns_array = np.diff(np.log(s))
    return (pd.Series(returns_array, index=s.index[1:]))

DAILY VOLATILITY¶

Bars per day? For the 1018 Dollar Bars we had in Part 1, there were counts of 335, 316, and 360 Dollar Bars over 3 one week periods of 5 trading days. Average bars per day is (335+316+360)/15 = 67 bars Trading period is 5pm Sun to 5pm Fri = 5 days. Therefore we would use a span0 value of 67 when calling getDailyVolatility. Here we are using a Dollar threshold of 27465 on different data, though, and that data trades 24/7. So we need to recalculate the average # of Dollar Bars per day.

NOTE: ptS1 of [1, 2] describes the horizontal barrier - in this particular case the profit-taking barrier is half x the stop-loss barrier

  • trgt: The unit width of the horizontal barriers.
  • ptSl: A list of two non-negative float values:
    • ptSl[0]: The factor that multiplies trgt to set the width of the upper barrier. If 0, there will not be an upper barrier.
    • ptSl[1]: The factor that multiplies trgt to set the width of the lower barrier. If 0, there will not be a lower barrier.

Let's look at some Technical Analysis methods we might use: MA Crossover, the RSI Indicator and the Aroon Indicator.

MA CROSSOVER¶

A crossover is the most basic type of signal and is favored among many traders because it removes all emotion. The most basic type of crossover is when the price of an asset moves from one side of a moving average and closes on the other. Price crossovers are used by traders to identify shifts in momentum and can be used as a basic entry or exit strategy. This is often implemented with a fast (short-term) moving average and a "slow" (long =-term moving average). A cross of the fast MA below the slow MA from above can signal the beginning of a downtrend and would likely be used by traders as a signal to close out any existing long positions and possibly go short. Conversely, a close of the fast MA above the slow MA from below may suggest the beginning of a new uptrend and signal going long.

Now, let's apply the above labeling/triple-barrier method to some meta-labelling of a specific feature like MA crossover. The idea is that once we have this working we can extend it to other technical indicators such as RSI, Bollinger Bands, etc.

Based on the Serial Correlation example in Part 1 (Notebook 1.0-bk-data-exploration_of_bar_types.ipynb), we found that Volume Bars have the lowest Serial Correlation and also have positive peaks at 3 and 6 lag periods.

With this new data we have switched to Dollar Bars for reasons mentioned earlier. With larger datasets the computation of autocorrelation is intensive and lengthy, so we are going to use 8/21 period MA crossover for no reason other than these are Fibonacci numbers.

Sources:

* https://www.investopedia.com/university/movingaverage/movingaverages4.asp

Below, we perform an asof merge to get the side onto the return and bin information above. This is similar to a left-join except that we match on nearest key rather than equal keys.

Both DataFrames must be sorted by the key.

For each row in the left DataFrame:

* A backward search selects the last row in the right DataFrame whose on key is less than or equal to the lefts key.
* A forward search selects the first row in the right DataFrame whose on key is greater than or equal to the lefts key.
* A nearest search selects the row in the right DataFrame whose on key is closest in absolute distance to the lefts key.

What is the explanation here? Consider the first row, "2015-02-02 07:18:00 0.012494 1.0 1" - this was trading on the buy side, {1} the return was positive and g.t. the minRet threshold, so it goes in bin {1}, i.e. successful trade. Consider the row "2015-02-03 08:41:00 -0.046545 0.0 1" - this was also trading on the buy side and the return was negative (not above the threshold), so it goes in bin {0}, i.e. labelled as a failed trade. This is how we wrangle the data into a format suitable for a binary classifier such as a random forest.

The model (crossing of ma 8/21) has determined the side to trade: {-1,1} (short and long). This is a general idea of engineering the feature according to de Prado's suggested methods. We can now train a Random Forest classifier to decide whether to use this feature to trade or not, i.e. a decision {1,0}. Here we plot the ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) curve.

An ROC curve (receiver operating characteristic curve) is a graph showing the performance of a classification model at all classification thresholds. This curve plots two parameters:

* True Positive Rate (synonym for recall)
* False Positive Rate

We also compute the AUC value, which is the area under the curve. AUC measures how true positive rate (recall) and false positive rate trade off. More importantly, AUC is not a function of threshold. It is an evaluation of the classifier as threshold varies over all possible values. It is in a sense a broader metric, testing the quality of the internal value that the classifier generates and then compares to a threshold. It is not testing the quality of a particular choice of threshold.

We perform similar metrics for the other technial features: RSI, Aroon.

Source:

* https://developers.google.com/machine-learning/crash-course/classification/roc-and-auc

RSI¶

Create a function for computing 14-period RSI. The Relative Strength Index - RSI - is a momentum indicator that measures the magnitude of recent price changes to analyze overbought or oversold conditions. It is primarily used to attempt to identify overbought or oversold conditions in the trading of an asset. Reasoning behind this identification: the RSI going below 30 indicates an oversold condition, and so a move back above 30 can be a signal to buy. Conversely, RSI above 70 indicates an overbought condition and a move back below 70 can be a signal to sell.

For each trading period an upward change U or downward change D is calculated. Up periods are characterized by the close being higher than the previous close:

Conversely, a down period is characterized by the close being lower than the previous period's close (note that D is nonetheless a positive number),

If the last close is the same as the previous, both U and D are zero. The average U and D are calculated using an n-period smoothed or modified moving average (SMMA or MMA) which is an exponentially smoothed Moving Average with = 1/period. Some commercial packages, like AIQ, use a standard exponential moving average (EMA) as the average instead of Wilder's SMMA. Here we use a simple MA, or a rolling mean.

Wilder originally formulated the calculation of the moving average as: newval = (prevval * (period - 1) + newdata) / period. This is fully equivalent to the aforementioned exponential smoothing. New data is simply divided by period which is equal to the alpha calculated value of 1/period. Previous average values are modified by (period -1)/period which in effect is period/period - 1/period and finally 1 - 1/period which is 1 - alpha.

The ratio of these averages is the relative strength or relative strength factor:

If the average of D values is zero, then according to the equation, the RS value will approach infinity, so that the resulting RSI, as computed below, will approach 100.

The relative strength factor is then converted to a relative strength index between 0 and 100.

The smoothed moving averages should be appropriately initialized with a simple moving average using the first n values in the price series.

Sources:

* https://www.investopedia.com/terms/r/rsi.asp

AROON¶

The Aroon Indicator was developed by Tushar S. Chande. It is a technical indicator that is used to identify when trends are likely to change direction. In essence, the indicator measures the time it takes for the price to reach the highest and lowest points over a given timeframe as a percentage of total time. The indicator consists of the "Aroon up" line, which measures the strength of the uptrend, and the "Aroon down" line, which measures the strength of the downtrend.

The two component lines are calculated as follows:

* Aroon Up - ((N - Days Since N-day High) / N) x 100
* Aroon Down - ((N - Days Since N-day Low) / N) x 100

The N is the number of periods used for the indicator. By default, many traders use the Aroon indicator over 25 periods. To simplify calculation and save time, I have used the ta-lib implementation here. TA-lib is an excellent and somewhat under-rated Python library that all MSFE students should probably know about.

NOTE: There's something special and unusual about this implementation. It is non-standard because - typically - Aroon is based on high and low of price bars. In this case we are letting it loose on high and low volume of a volume bar, not price. So it might be unique in this respect. But sometimes you have to come up with new ideas of your own. Our volume bars consider only volume not price at a specific volume; the only price given with them is ClosePrice which is the price at the closing volume of the volume bar. Hopefully this makes sense.

Source: https://www.investopedia.com/articles/trading/06/aroon.asp

def returns(s):
    arr = np.diff(np.log(s))
    return (pd.Series(arr, index=s.index[1:]))

def df_rolling_autocorrelation(df, window, lag=1):
    """Compute rolling column-wise autocorrelation for a DataFrame."""

    return (df.rolling(window=window)
            .corr(df.shift(lag))) # could .dropna() here

Combining features into a dataset for an actual model.¶

Here we take the strongest features (in terms of AUC, Accuracy, Classification, ROC characteristics) and combine them into a dataframe that we can use in a Random Forest Classifier. This is equivalent to finding the strongest signals from a combination of features. Aroon and RSI were the strongest predictors of signals, followed by MA so we'll use all 3, using Aroon to provide the target volatility because MA and RSI have a similar number of signals either side {1, -1} and we infer that many of them will align.

Fortunately, scikit-learn comes with sklearn.model_selection.RandomizedSearchCV and sklearn.model_selection.GridSearchCV which allows us to perform randomized and grid searches on hyperparameters. We also import StratifiedKFold in order to perform K-Fold Cross-Validation.

In [86]:
# n_estimators controls the number of trees in the random forest
# Here we step 10 between 200 and 2000
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 200, stop = 2000, num = 10)]

# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']

# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 11)]
max_depth.append(None)

# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]

# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]

# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
bootstrap = [True, False]

# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}

Stratification seeks to ensure that each fold is representative of all strata of the data. Generally this is done in a supervised way for classification and aims to ensure each class is (approximately) equally represented across each test fold (which are of course combined in a complementary way to form training folds).

The intuition behind this relates to the bias of most classification algorithms. They tend to weight each instance equally which means overrepresented classes get too much weight (e.g. optimizing F-measure, Accuracy or a complementary form of error).

Using Stratified K-Fold cross-validation, we have improved the mean area under the curve slightly over the grid_search model (0.55 +/- 0.07, vs 0.566). Given the standard deviation from the mean AUC of +/- 0.07, this is only a small improvement; a little more of the Mean ROC is above the "luck line". We do not believe we can improve the model beyond an AUC of 0.566 or accuracy 0.554 (55.4%).

Below we obtain the last 92 rows of our Xy data that represent our out-of-sample test set, and append the predicted bin value (y_pred_opt_gs) as "pred_bin". Then add the ClosePrice from the corresponding volume bar as "close_price". That way we can calculate actual returns (from combining real returns with the desired bin values) and predicted returns (from combining real returns with the bin values predicted by our model on our out-of-sample data), using a simple vectorized backtest. One problem with the combined model is that it only predicts whether to trade or not, it does not determine a side. So we will compute returns for all long trades, and all short trades separately. For short trades we multiply the binary value by -1. We will explain this challgnge and how we might handle side prediction further in our report.

Here, "real_returns" represents buy and hold over the period of the 92 dollar bars in the test set; "actual_returns" represents what the returns from our model would be if it was 100% accurate - i.e. if it matched the binary output from our Xy dataset, and "pred_returns" represents the returns the model's predictions generated. For the long-only results, we are doing better than buy and hold, but crucially with less exposure and a lower standard deviation. Even though the model achieved a binary prediction accuracy of 55.4%, it seemed to do so in such a way that left out a lot of the bad trades! For the short-only results, sell and hold short BTC would have done best but, we are not sure if BTC is a shortable instrument, unless you completely hedged your BTC by converting it to dollars at the start of the period and converted it back to BTC at the end, which may be impractical and exposes you to currency risk also.

# total number of days in results (need to compute because it is not time bars)
days = (results.index[-1:] - results.index[:1]).days.values[0]
# 11.55 is the percent return for long-only over the period (see above). Let's calculate annual returns

return_per_day_pred_l = 0.1155 / days
stdev_per_day_pred_l = 0.059908

annualized_return_pred_l = ((return_per_day_pred_l + 1)**365) - 1
print("Annualized Return of Predicted Trades (Long-only):  %.2f %%" % (annualized_return_pred_l * 100))

# Annualized Standard Deviation = Standard Deviation of Returns * Square Root (250)
annualized_stdev_pred_l = stdev_per_day_pred_l * 252**0.5
print("Annualized Std Dev of Predicted Trades (Long-only):  %.5f" % (annualized_stdev_pred_l))

# Sharpe Ratio is return/volatility (assume risk-free rate negligible)
sharpe = annualized_return_pred_l / annualized_stdev_pred_l
print("Sharpe Ratio of our model (Long-only): %.2f" % sharpe)
